    "is decidable for an agent A, if it is decidable whether A herself would accept X if it were performed by another agent B given input Y.",
    "For instance, if X given Y causes harm, and A would not want others to cause her harm, the answer is decidedly no.",
    "Of course, while this sort of analysis ignores the complexity involved in the determining the de facto mappings between any possible input, action, and outcome, it gives a general structure which can be analyzed:",
    "(GR1) Golden Rule based on one's own preferences 61 For instance, the GR might refer to a set of actions and individual preferences of an acting agent A, in the sense that A has to check whether the individual actions satisfy her individual preferences: she will treat others (act) based on how she likes others to treat her (i.e., how an action, if performed by someone else, would affect her own preferences).",
    "Given that the agent can quickly check how actions affect her preferences, the worst-case time complexity of deciding whether any action is morally permissible is O(np), where n is the number of possible actions and p is the number of preferences."
